<font color="#FF0000">THANKS FOR THE MEMORIES</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct  9  2:00:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Lin:<br><br>
I respect your status as a woman, human being and an <br>
American citizen.  You have the right to free speech, assembly and to protest the workings of this government ...bear in mind that military force assures those rights.. not simply an idealistic pursuit of &quot;wishing and wanting.&quot;<br><br>
I have no idea how mature you were in high school.. what peer pressures came to bear on you to influence your decision to protest the war in Vietnam.  Only you know the real reasons... I know and feel the results.<br><br>
There are no good wars that should be fought!  However, there are motivations such as greed, religious fanaticism, bigotry, hatred, control freaks and need for power that make people and groups of people square off... lose their communication skills.. and start killing each other.  Almost always, people who advocate war are people who do not have to fight in them... except for some who may have a masculine identity problem and need to prove themselves.<br><br>
It is easy for someone to focus upon what they like or dislike about a war.. while it is going on and in retrospect.<br><br>
If you were to bake cookies to feed the poor.. because you did not want them to starve.  I could chose to applaud you or.. I could condemn you for wasting our household resources.  If I bickered enough.. you may have turned out a batch of pretty sorry cookies.. which were not given to the starving poor but sold to them by the very grocer who sold you the ingredients.  You get shamed... the grocer gets rich ..and all I did was screw up your good intentions.<br><br>
I did not bake cookies.. but I did engage in two years of intensive combat to gain freedom for others while you and others caused indecision in the kitchen.  Don't be so naive to assume that you saved anybody's life.. instead I would like for you to contemplate your contributions to prolonging the war.. costing the lives of thousands of American fighting men and women and hundreds of thousands of Vietnamese people, men, women and children.  Also, I would like for you to weight the impact that you and yours had upon the returning traumatized combatants who desperately needed everything but what you gave them... REJECTION!<br><br>
I feel that it is appropriate that you should cry at the wall.  Try crying for me.. I am unable to go there... I wouldn't be able to walk away.<br><br>
I respect and love you and those whom you love.  I am glad that you exercise your human rights.. I still wish the Vietnamese had what you enjoy today.  My efforts and those of my dead and living brothers to buy it for them was negated somewhat by your efforts.  If you can live with it.. I can live without it.<br><br>
Captain Edward Ramon - Republic of Vietnam (1966-67-69)<br><br>

